            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Thank you @juditnovak for your investigation into ST’s response to termcodes, this points out only one incompatibility with ST, which can be easily addressed in NeoVim’s configuration as per @justinmk’s suggestion:\n\n### Improved Method A\nRecreate **Steps to reproduce** with `$TERM=xterm-256color` via **Method A**, with the addition of these two commands, suggested by @justinmk.\n\n`:highlight dCursor guibg=#f8f8f2 `\n`:autocmd VimLeave * set guicursor=a:dCursor `\n#### Outcome\n NeoVim does in fact “reset” the cursor colour to the terminal’s default after exiting.\n\n### Therefore, workaround for the issue:\nNeoVim configuration to achieve desired behaviour in ST with `$TERM=xterm-256color`\n```\n-- Define cursor highlights\nvim.cmd.highlight({\"dCursor\", \"guibg=#f8f8f2\"}) -- default dracula foreground for Normal mode (& terminal default)\nvim.cmd.highlight({\"iCursor\", \"guibg=#a9b665\"}) -- gruvbox material green for Insert mode\nvim.cmd.highlight({\"rCursor\", \"guibg=#e78a4e\"}) -- gruvbox material orange for Replace mode\nvim.cmd.highlight({\"vCursor\", \"guibg=#ea6962\"}) -- gruvbox material red for Visual mode\nvim.cmd.highlight({\"cCursor\", \"guibg=#7daea3\"}) -- gruvbox material blue for Command modes\n-- Apply appropriate cursor highlight depending on mode\nvim.opt.guicursor = \"a:block-dCursor,i:block-iCursor,v:block-vCursor,c-ci-cr:block-cCursor,r:block-rCursor\"\n\n-- Force terminal default color on exit\nvim.api.nvim_create_autocmd(\"VimLeave\", {\n  pattern = \"*\",\n  command = \"set guicursor=a:dCursor\",\n})\n```\nThis nicely encapsulates the cursor color management to NeoVim until it restores it and hands off control to ST. \n\n### TL;DR / Conclusion\n**ST can handle termcodes for cursor color changes**, and with `$TERM=xterm-256color` the cursor color can be changed in ST by NeoVim, with a workaround for resetting the cursor color to terminal default. \n### TODO\n_So the milestone is for NeoVim to recognize this termcode capability in ST/set it as it does for some other terminals in [tui.c](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/master/src/nvim/tui/tui.c), so that this works with `$TERM=st-256color`and so that it treats ST on par with xterm in this regard (except changing back the curosr color with `ESC]112ESC\\` maybe)_\n\nNotably, the fix from #7641 apparently does not help this, \nhttps://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/9cc060218b66c600f7f50ecbec5ba6f1b3a9da82/src/nvim/tui/tui.c#L2211-L2211\nbut something of the sort will probably do. \nI'm generally not too familiar with NeoVim's source code, but unless somebody is willing to do this, I would appreciate any advice to try add it myself.",
