        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "That `|| st` condition is about \"cursor style\" (shape), not \"cursor color\".\n\n`set_cursor_color` decides cursor color. And https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/e71d2c817d1a2475551f58a98e411f6b39a5be3f/src/nvim/tui/tui.c#L2373 hints that the terminfo entries are `Cr` and `Cs`. \n\nNvim's builtin terminfo for xterm has those entries: https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/e71d2c817d1a2475551f58a98e411f6b39a5be3f/src/nvim/tui/terminfo_defs.h#L2783-L2784\n\nbut the builtin for `st` does not: https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/e71d2c817d1a2475551f58a98e411f6b39a5be3f/src/nvim/tui/terminfo_defs.h#L1410\n\nThose builtin terminfos are generated from ncurses.\n\n# Solution\n\nDo one of the following:\n\n- ask Thomas Dickey to add the entires to the ncurses definitions\n- add a special-case for `st` in Nvim's `augment_terminfo()`\n\nboth of those assume that `st` *always* supports this stuff, *or* at least it doesn't barf when it receives unknown termcodes (I can't remember how it behaves in that case, please confirm).\n\nIf the above isn't true, then the only solution is to update your own system terminfo for `st`. Nvim will read it based on `$TERM`. (Don't ask how to do this, it's been well-covered in `:help terminfo`, the issue tracker, and chatgpt.)",
